Steps and tasks:¶

1. Import the necessary libraries 
2. Read the data as a data frame 
3. Perform basic EDA which should include the following and print out your insights at every step. 
    a. Shape of the data  
    b. Data type of each attribute  
    c. Checking the presence of missing values 
    d. 5 Point summary of numerical attributes 
    e. Checking the presence of outliers 
4. Prepare the data to train a model – check if data types are appropriate, get rid of the missing values etc. 
5. Train a few standard classification algorithms, note and comment on their performances across different classification metrics. 
6. Build the ensemble models and compare the results with the base models. Note: Random forest can be used only with Decision trees.
7. Compare performances of all the models

        bank_df[feature] = pd.Categorical(bank_df[feature])# Replace strings with an integer

Split Data¶

In [17]:
X = bank_df.drop("Target" , axis=1)
y = bank_df.pop("Target")
In [18]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=.30, random_state=1)

5. Train a few standard classification algorithms, note and comment on their performances across different classification metrics¶

Logistic regression¶

Let us first try logistic regression to predict the personal will subscribe a term deposit or not

print(metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_predict))

Recall (true positives / (true positives + false negatives)) for class 1 is the least. That is because majority of data points belong to class 0 and in KNN, probability of finding data points from class 0 closer to a test point than a data point from class 1 is high.

Build Decision Tree Model¶

We will build our model using the DecisionTreeClassifier function. Using default 'gini' criteria to split. Other option include 'entropy'

In [25]:

dTree.fit(X_train, y_train)

Reducing over fitting (Regularization)¶

In [29]:
dTreeR = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion = 'gini', max_depth = 3, random_state=1)
dTreeR.fit(X_train, y_train)
print(dTreeR.score(X_train, y_train))
print(dTreeR.score(X_test, y_test))

0.9005276961481341
0.9019463285166618

Limiting the max depth has reduced removed the over fitting and score is also good.

6. Build the ensemble models and compare the results with the base models. Note: Random forest can be used only with Decision trees.¶

Ensemble Learning - Bagging¶

In [34]:
bgcl = BaggingClassifier(base_estimator=dTree, n_estimators=50,random_state=1)
bgcl = bgcl.fit(X_train, y_train)
In [35]:
y_predict = bgcl.predict(X_test)

print(bgcl.score(X_test , y_test))

Ensemble Learning - AdaBoost¶

In [36]:
#abcl = AdaBoostClassifier(base_estimator=dTree, n_estimators=10)
abcl = AdaBoostClassifier( n_estimators=50)
abcl = abcl.fit(X_train, y_train)

In contrary to Bagging for boosting the principle is that we should take simple base model. Now if we take dTree as base estimator which it self is very complex as we see above the Performance decrease to nearly 87.2% Now if we allow AsaBoostClassifier to select default base_estimator ot select some very simple Model and performance increse to 90.04%

Ensemble Learning- RandomForest Classifier¶

In [40]:
rfcl = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = 50, random_state=1,max_features=10)
rfcl = rfcl.fit(X_train, y_train)

Random Forest classier is essentially follows the Bagging principle and use starts with Complex base model. The max_feature is very important for otimizing the performace of the model. there are nearly 33 columns so by default the value should be near about square root of 33 i.e 6. But varying the value from 6 to 12 we find 10 gives the best performance.

In [41]:
